# Deployment

## Overview
A release is the set of changes the next user will see. This skill enforces
a green suite precondition, an artifact fingerprint that identifies what
actually shipped, and a rollback path that is rehearsed — not assumed.

## When to Use
- **Trigger**: {{WHEN_TRIGGER}}
- **Not when**: {{WHEN_NOT}}
- **Related skills**: `db-migration` (schema changes must ship with a down
  migration in the same release window), `api-endpoint` (new endpoints
  gate on the contract doc being released with the code).

## TDD Focus
- **Must test**: The full project test suite must be green on the exact
  artifact SHA being released. Smoke-check the deployed artifact against a
  minimal post-deploy assertion (health endpoint, CLI `--version`, static
  asset hash, etc.).
- **Test exempt**: None — "release the code, skip the tests" is the scenario
  this skill exists to prevent.
- **Coverage target**: Full suite green. Coverage thresholds from
  individual features are inherited; no release-specific override.

## Process
### Step 1: Confirm the release SHA is clean
{{PROCESS_STEP_1}}

### Step 2: Build the artifact
{{PROCESS_STEP_2}}

### Step 3: Run the full test suite on the artifact
{{PROCESS_STEP_3}}

### Step 4: Deploy + post-deploy smoke
{{PROCESS_STEP_4}}

### Step 5: Record release metadata
Write the release SHA, artifact fingerprint, deploy time, and rollback
command into the release log (CHANGELOG.md or equivalent). This is the
evidence used if incident-response needs to identify what shipped.

### Step 6: Rehearse rollback (dry-run)
Execute the rollback command against a non-production target or a
staging artifact. Confirm it runs to completion and produces the pre-release
state. Do not deploy to production until this has been observed green at
least once.

## Common Rationalizations
| Excuse | Rebuttal |
|--------|----------|
| "Staging was green, I can skip re-running the suite on the artifact" | Staging and the release artifact can diverge (config, secrets, build flags). The test suite runs on the artifact SHA or the release does not ship. |
| "The rollback is simple — I don't need to rehearse" | The first time a rollback is executed, it finds the gap no one anticipated (missing secret, migration-down needed, cache poisoned). Rehearse once, ship many. |
| "We haven't needed a rollback in months, so the path is probably fine" | Unused paths rot. DNS, credentials, artifact stores, and access tokens all drift. "Probably fine" is how 3 AM pages start. |
| "Deploying the DB migration and the code in two separate deploys is safer" | Not if the code assumes the new shape. Two-step deploys require a code version that handles both old and new shapes simultaneously — that is an extra feature you must also ship. Default to one unit. |

## Red Flags
- Release SHA differs from the tested SHA (tests ran against a different build)
- No post-deploy smoke evidence in the release log
- Rollback command recorded but never executed end-to-end, even once
- Feature flags toggled on in the release with no flag-off verification
- DB migration shipped without the matching down migration being present at the release SHA

## Verification
- [ ] Release SHA matches the SHA the full test suite passed on (evidence: CI log + artifact metadata)
- [ ] Post-deploy smoke assertion passed against the live target (evidence: smoke output, dated)
- [ ] Release log updated with SHA + fingerprint + rollback command (evidence: `git diff` on CHANGELOG.md or release doc)
- [ ] Rollback rehearsed at least once against a non-prod target in the last release window (evidence: rehearsal log)
- [ ] No un-merged migration down path at the release SHA (evidence: forward/down pairing check)
